from Herder through Goethe to Hegel, championed human agency in self-determination while working out the social and political implications of our creation in the image of God. While bildung was invoked to justify racism and colonialism by stigmatizing those deemed resistant to self-cultivation, it also nourished ideals of dialogical encounter and mutual recognition. Herdt reveals how the project of forming humanity lives on in our ongoing efforts to grapple with this complicated legacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBildungsromansxHistory and criticism. 0aBildungsromans-History and criticism. 0aHumanismzGermanyxHistoryy18th century. 0aHumanismzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aHumanism-Germany-History-18th century. 0aHumanism-Germany-History-19th century. 0aMoral developmentzGermany. 0aMoral development-Germany. 0aPhilosophy and religionzGermanyxHistoryy18th century. 0aPhilosophy and religionzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aPhilosophy and religion-Germany-History-18th century. 0aPhilosophy and religion-Germany-History-19th century. 0aPhilosophy, Germany18th century. 0aPhilosophy, Germany19th century. 0aPhilosophy, German-18th century. 0aPhilosophy, German-19th century. 0aReligion and culture. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aBildung.  aFriedrich Schiller.  aGeorg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel.  aJohann Gottfried Herder.  aJohann Wolfgang von Goethe.  aKarl Barth.  aWilhelm von Humboldt.  aempire.  ahumanism.  asecularization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig. Stud., Jewish Stud.2019 Englishz978311061074108iTitl